{
  "text": "In univariate order selection, the given values of \u03b1 would often select an overfit order higher than 37 for N = 5000. In particular, \u03b1 = 1.25 and \u03b1 = 1.5 would give a high probability of overfit [CITATION_1] . This demonstrates that the probability of overfit is smaller for multichannel vector data than for univariate data.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "40805392"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "40805392": {
      "title": "On the penalty factor for autoregressive order selection in finite samples",
      "abstract": "The order selection criterion that selects models with the smallest squared error of prediction is the best. The finite sample theory describes equivalents for asymptotic order selection criteria that are bet- ter in the hite sample practice. This correction for finite sample statistics is the most important. Afterwards, a preference in order selection criteria can be obtained by computing an optimal value for the penalty factor based on a subjective balance of the risks of overfitting and underfitting."
    }
  }
}